Cross-conformal predictors Vladimir Vovk v.vovk @rhul.ac.uk http://vovk.net August 6, 2012 Abstract This note introduces the method of cross-conformal prediction, which is a hybrid of the methods of inductive conformal prediction and cross- validation, and studies its validity and predictive eciency empirically.

The on-board instrument SWAP (Katsiyanni, Berghman, and Swap Consortium, 2010) observes the Sun in ex- treme ultraviolet at 17.4 nm, whereas LYRA ( http://proba2.oma.be/index.html/ science/ ) monitors the solar irradiance in the wavelength range from soft X-rays to ultraviolet.

The CME initiation and propagation at the initial stage have been studied using SDO/AIA data and FITS images of the Sun ( http://jsoc.stanford.edu/ajax/ lookdata.html ), data processing level 1 in EUV lines = 17:1nmand 21.1 nm that are formed when plasma temperature is 9 105 K and 2 106 K. To analyse the CME kinematics, we used calibrated solar images ( http://proba2.oma.be/ swap/data/bsd ) taken by SWAP in the emission line having a wavelength of 17.4 SOLA: paper.tex; 24 December 2013; 10:28; p. 3

Data ( http://sharpp.nrl.navy.mil/cgi-bin/swdbi/lasco/images/form ) from Large Angle and Spectrometric Coronagraphs (LASCO) aboard SOHO were used to examine the CME propagation at distances R > 2R0(Ris counted from the centre of the solar disc in the plane of the sky, R0is the solar radius).

To get information about soft X-ray emission, we used data from Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellites (GOES) ( http://goes.ngdc.noaa.gov/data ) and PROBA2/LYRA ( http://proba2.oma.be/index.html/science ).

Information about eruptive laments (prominence) from the closest proximity to the CME generation region was provided by the telescopes observing the Sun in the H-alpha line ( http://swrl.njit.edu/ghn web/ ) and by Coronado SolarMax H-alpha Imager at Mauna Loa Solar Observatory (MLSO) ( http://mlso.hao.ucar.
In the eld of view of LASCO coronagraphs, we determined the HCME front position from the catalogue ( http://cdaw.gsfc.nasa.gov/CME list).

It illustrates the lament (prominence) eruption from the region of the CME initiation, according to H-alpha line observations (data from Kanzelhohe Solar Observatory http://www.kso.ac.at/index en.php ) (there are no H-alpha data during the onset of the lament eruption).
